00:50:24.630 --> 00:50:27.240
niched as a consumer
entertainment device that's

00:50:27.240 --> 00:50:29.780
not appropriate for business,
and it would have been stuck

00:50:29.780 --> 00:50:31.920
in the same position that
Macintosh was in for a long

00:50:31.920 --> 00:50:33.100
time relative to Windows.

00:50:33.100 --> 00:50:34.560
Windows is right for
business, Macintosh

00:50:34.560 --> 00:50:36.010
is right for creatives.

00:50:36.010 --> 00:50:38.680
Creative market is this big,
business market is this big.

00:50:38.680 --> 00:50:42.070
Instead, RIM tried to chase
Apple, made itself a bad

00:50:42.070 --> 00:50:44.810
business tool and a bad
entertainment tool at the same

00:50:44.810 --> 00:50:46.820
time, really cratered
the business.

00:50:46.820 --> 00:50:50.530
So my usual answer is, know what
you're best at, know who

00:50:50.530 --> 00:50:53.840
your customers are, stay the
course, do a great job of

00:50:53.840 --> 00:50:54.530
differentiating.

00:50:54.530 --> 00:50:56.340
Don't try to own
100% of market.

00:50:56.340 --> 00:50:58.360
Own your segment of the market,
and don't worry about

00:50:58.360 --> 00:50:59.410
the rest of it.

00:50:59.410 --> 00:51:01.050
And that's what I
would have done.

00:51:01.050 --> 00:51:06.510
AUDIENCE: I'm wondering what
determines the company pick,

00:51:06.510 --> 00:51:08.410
either the visionary
or the analytical.

00:51:08.410 --> 00:51:10.020
Is it because of the leader, or

00:51:10.020 --> 00:51:12.260
because of certain segments?

00:51:12.260 --> 00:51:13.630
MICHAEL MACE: How does a company
end up being either

00:51:13.630 --> 00:51:16.070
visionary or analytical?

00:51:16.070 --> 00:51:18.490
There are different industries
that have different balance.

00:51:18.490 --> 00:51:21.250
So for instance, if you look at
the entertainment industry,

00:51:21.250 --> 00:51:23.840
most of them, even though they
try to be analytical, most of

00:51:23.840 --> 00:51:25.190
them are vision driven.

00:51:25.190 --> 00:51:27.420
They just don't know which
movies are going to make it.

00:51:27.420 --> 00:51:30.200
And it's their gut feeling
about, I trust this director,

00:51:30.200 --> 00:51:31.820
I trust this producer,
or this is what I

00:51:31.820 --> 00:51:33.590
think is a good direction.

00:51:33.590 --> 00:51:36.580
Now, they do sometimes behave
like analytical companies in

00:51:36.580 --> 00:51:38.536
the sense that they'll all try
to copy each other if one of

00:51:38.536 --> 00:51:39.470
them's successful.

00:51:39.470 --> 00:51:41.680
Oh, Tolkien movie did well.

00:51:41.680 --> 00:51:44.410
Let's all do fantasy
movies about elves.

00:51:44.410 --> 00:51:46.890
And you get a bunch of things
like that, so you do get some

00:51:46.890 --> 00:51:47.840
of that behavior.

00:51:47.840 --> 00:51:50.530
But still, you get some
industries that are much more

00:51:50.530 --> 00:51:51.920
visionary than others.

00:51:51.920 --> 00:51:54.520
However what usually drives
it is the founders.

00:51:54.520 --> 00:51:57.400
And you can have founders who
are very vision driven, like a

00:51:57.400 --> 00:51:58.610
Steve Jobs.

00:51:58.610 --> 00:51:59.290
He's just ego.

00:51:59.290 --> 00:52:00.370
Force of will, man.

00:52:00.370 --> 00:52:02.580
He decided he was right, and you
were going to follow him,

00:52:02.580 --> 00:52:05.290
and that's what it
was going to be.

00:52:05.290 --> 00:52:08.120
You get other companies that
have a more analytical point

00:52:08.120 --> 00:52:10.740
of view in their founders, and
that tends to color the

00:52:10.740 --> 00:52:12.170
behavior of the whole company.

00:52:12.170 --> 00:52:15.940
Why does Google focus so much
on testing things and

00:52:15.940 --> 00:52:17.420
analyzing things and
stuff like that?

00:52:17.420 --> 00:52:20.800
Well, you've got some guys
who are trained PhDs in

00:52:20.800 --> 00:52:23.080
engineering who have a really
strong science background, and

00:52:23.080 --> 00:52:25.470
that's how they're trained to
think about things and to

00:52:25.470 --> 00:52:26.470
approach problems.

00:52:26.470 --> 00:52:28.910
And like I said, one isn't
better than the other.

00:52:28.910 --> 00:52:31.190
The big thing is, understand
which one you are, do a really

00:52:31.190 --> 00:52:33.510
good job of executing on it,
but then watch your blind

00:52:33.510 --> 00:52:36.450
side, which is what this
road map thing's about.

00:52:36.450 --> 00:52:39.466
AUDIENCE: Something I really
like about Google here is we

00:52:39.466 --> 00:52:43.080
are given the opportunity to
criticize, to say we don't

00:52:43.080 --> 00:52:46.060
like things.

00:52:46.060 --> 00:52:47.760
But now, the question
is, how to get that

00:52:47.760 --> 00:52:50.230
into actionable items?

00:52:50.230 --> 00:52:55.050
We are good criticizers, but
I'm not sure we change the

00:52:55.050 --> 00:52:56.730
road, the path.

00:52:56.730 --> 00:52:59.360
MICHAEL MACE: So being able to
criticize well versus being

00:52:59.360 --> 00:53:01.480
able to actually drive action.

00:53:01.480 --> 00:53:05.270
So I'm on the outside, and so I
have a blind spot to how the

00:53:05.270 --> 00:53:07.800
details of decision making
processes work within Google,

00:53:07.800 --> 00:53:10.080
because you guys are very
careful to keep that sort of

00:53:10.080 --> 00:53:12.390
internal stuff confidential.

00:53:12.390 --> 00:53:14.720
So what I'll say in general, and
this is just about dealing

00:53:14.720 --> 00:53:17.280
with human beings in general,
especially if you're in an

00:53:17.280 --> 00:53:20.180
analytical culture, is you
can't just critique.

00:53:20.180 --> 00:53:22.530
You've got to be persuasive.

00:53:22.530 --> 00:53:25.300
The more you can flesh out the
reason that you're critiquing

00:53:25.300 --> 00:53:28.960
something, what is the reasoning
behind it, the more

00:53:28.960 --> 00:53:30.400
that people are going to
tend to listen to it.

00:53:30.400 --> 00:53:32.300
Now, th e problem is going to
be, if you've got a visionary

00:53:32.300 --> 00:53:34.840
idea that you're trying to
critique from a visionary

00:53:34.840 --> 00:53:38.110
perspective, that's a really
hard thing to get across in

00:53:38.110 --> 00:53:40.320
any company that tends to be
analytical, because it's just

00:53:40.320 --> 00:53:41.420
my opinion.

00:53:41.420 --> 00:53:44.600
It's like, because of the
scientific method, you always

00:53:44.600 --> 00:53:45.760
listen to critiques.

00:53:45.760 --> 00:53:47.010
That's absolutely fine.

00:53:47.010 --> 00:53:49.420
I would expect Google to be a
great place for people doing

00:53:49.420 --> 00:53:51.180
criticism, because that's
how scientists

00:53:51.180 --> 00:53:51.770
are supposed to work.

00:53:51.770 --> 00:53:53.000
Peer review, right?

00:53:53.000 --> 00:53:56.250
We toss our ideas around, we
peer review, you fire away,

00:53:56.250 --> 00:53:58.260
you throw things at me, et
cetera, et cetera, et cetera.

00:53:58.260 --> 00:54:02.160
However, ultimately, peer review
you listen to, and then

00:54:02.160 --> 00:54:06.210
you're allowed to dismiss
it if you're in charge.

00:54:06.210 --> 00:54:07.930
A lot of it depends
on the managers

00:54:07.930 --> 00:54:10.190
above, and do they listen?

00:54:10.190 --> 00:54:12.520
Do they force the people who
are making the decisions to

00:54:12.520 --> 00:54:15.400
actually take into account
criticism?

00:54:15.400 --> 00:54:18.070
And then it's how persuasive can
the person who's doing the

00:54:18.070 --> 00:54:19.230
criticism be.

00:54:19.230 --> 00:54:21.670
And part of that is thinking
about this roadmap process.

00:54:21.670 --> 00:54:24.490
OK, why do you criticize it?

00:54:24.490 --> 00:54:25.970
Why do you think it's wrong?

00:54:25.970 --> 00:54:28.110
How much of those perspectives--
if you look

00:54:28.110 --> 00:54:29.710
from all those different
perspectives, can you set up

00:54:29.710 --> 00:54:32.055
an intellectual framework for
explaining why it's wrong, as

00:54:32.055 --> 00:54:33.780
opposed to just saying,
here's my opinion?

00:54:33.780 --> 00:54:35.800
The more you can put a framework
around it, the

00:54:35.800 --> 00:54:39.120
better chance you have of
getting people to listen to it

00:54:39.120 --> 00:54:41.150
and listen to it constructively
in the sense

00:54:41.150 --> 00:54:43.410
of, OK, you've given me some
ideas to work on, as opposed

00:54:43.410 --> 00:54:44.990
to, oh, you're disagreeing
with me, you're

00:54:44.990 --> 00:54:46.010
messing with my job.

00:54:46.010 --> 00:54:48.070
I don't want to hear about
that sort of stuff.

00:54:48.070 --> 00:54:50.290
So think about how you could put
a framework around things.

00:54:50.290 --> 00:54:51.150
I apologize.

00:54:51.150 --> 00:54:53.320
I know that's really kind of a
vague answer, but that's the

00:54:53.320 --> 00:54:55.265
best I can do from a distance.

00:54:55.265 --> 00:54:57.600
But I'd be glad to talk to you
more about it offline, if you

00:54:57.600 --> 00:55:00.810
want to brainstorm sometime.

00:55:00.810 --> 00:55:02.710
AUDIENCE: First of all, I want
to say thank you for the talk.

00:55:02.710 --> 00:55:04.160
MICHAEL MACE: My pleasure.

00:55:04.160 --> 00:55:06.690
AUDIENCE: You had a lot of
really good examples of

00:55:06.690 --> 00:55:09.740
visionary companies and
analytical companies, but I

00:55:09.740 --> 00:55:12.220
was wondering, do you have any
examples of companies that

00:55:12.220 --> 00:55:15.030
have managed that
transition well?

00:55:15.030 --> 00:55:16.430
MICHAEL MACE: Companies that
have managed the transition

00:55:16.430 --> 00:55:18.240
from visionary to analytical?

00:55:18.240 --> 00:55:19.780
AUDIENCE: Or vice versa.

00:55:19.780 --> 00:55:20.143
MICHAEL MACE: Yeah.

00:55:20.143 --> 00:55:22.920
You know, I think HP, for a
long time, did it well.

00:55:22.920 --> 00:55:27.110
I mean, it was always an
engineering oriented company,

00:55:27.110 --> 00:55:28.740
so it was a little bit
analytical to begin with, but

00:55:28.740 --> 00:55:31.640
the founders had pretty strong
ideas about places they wanted

00:55:31.640 --> 00:55:34.100
to go, and they were willing to
place bets on those things,

00:55:34.100 --> 00:55:36.870
even if they didn't have a lot
of data backing it up.

00:55:36.870 --> 00:55:38.770
And I think for a long
time, HP did OK as

00:55:38.770 --> 00:55:39.580
an analytical company.

00:55:39.580 --> 00:55:42.540
They've lost their way today,
but if we talked about it 10

00:55:42.540 --> 00:55:44.660
years ago, I would've said
they're a pretty good model

00:55:44.660 --> 00:55:46.620
for how to make that go.

00:55:46.620 --> 00:55:49.420
3M is a really interesting one
to look at, because they're

00:55:49.420 --> 00:55:51.590
the closest to a company that's
both visionary and

00:55:51.590 --> 00:55:54.400
analytical, and really, I wish
I knew more about them.

00:55:54.400 --> 00:55:56.365
I've talked to some people from
3M about the processes

00:55:56.365 --> 00:55:57.510
that they use.

00:55:57.510 --> 00:56:01.050
What's interesting is they
can be very good at being

00:56:01.050 --> 00:56:05.200
analytical about understanding
how they identify engineering

00:56:05.200 --> 00:56:06.290
breakthroughs.

00:56:06.290 --> 00:56:08.320
They're really good at, for
instance, numerically being

00:56:08.320 --> 00:56:10.200
able to identify the most
creative engineers who are

00:56:10.200 --> 00:56:12.800
likely to produce the biggest
breakthroughs.

00:56:12.800 --> 00:56:14.350
They've done a great job of
getting through that.

00:56:14.350 --> 00:56:16.400
Really cool stuff, if
you haven't seen it.

00:56:16.400 --> 00:56:19.560
But they will tell you, trying
to figure out who can produce

00:56:19.560 --> 00:56:22.030
the breakthrough thinking on
a market as opposed to an

00:56:22.030 --> 00:56:24.610
engineering innovation,
they have no clue.

00:56:24.610 --> 00:56:26.650
It's like, I was talking
with one of them.

00:56:26.650 --> 00:56:28.520
It's like, we don't know.

00:56:28.520 --> 00:56:30.040
Like, maybe we look at
their track record.

00:56:30.040 --> 00:56:32.290
But of course, by the time you
look at their track record,

00:56:32.290 --> 00:56:34.400
they've already done it, and
you haven't grab those

00:56:34.400 --> 00:56:36.480
employees at the time when
they can help you out.

00:56:36.480 --> 00:56:40.950
So it's a real tricky one, and
other than HP, I have trouble

00:56:40.950 --> 00:56:43.556
thinking of a lot of other
really good examples.

00:56:43.556 --> 00:56:44.920
But good question.

00:56:44.920 --> 00:56:46.450
Thanks.

00:56:46.450 --> 00:56:49.550
AUDIENCE: So if you're working
in a strong, visionary

00:56:49.550 --> 00:56:53.660
company, right, and if I take
your recommendation on taking

00:56:53.660 --> 00:56:58.250
some analytical components to
balance it out, or at least to

00:56:58.250 --> 00:57:02.740
look at the other side of the
coin, right, what are the top

00:57:02.740 --> 00:57:06.810
talking points if you're talking
to an executive or

00:57:06.810 --> 00:57:11.000
whatever to basically make them
consider the other side

00:57:11.000 --> 00:57:11.400
of the coin?

00:57:11.400 --> 00:57:12.560
And again, vice versa, right?

00:57:12.560 --> 00:57:16.280
So if you're talking to an
executive in a company where

00:57:16.280 --> 00:57:19.080
they're very analytical, but
you're trying to basically

00:57:19.080 --> 00:57:22.830
sell this idea of incorporating
the other side

00:57:22.830 --> 00:57:24.720
of the coin, how
do you do that?

00:57:24.720 --> 00:57:28.080
What are the top three selling
points for each of those?

00:57:28.080 --> 00:57:29.040
MICHAEL MACE: Oh, that's
a great question.

00:57:29.040 --> 00:57:32.800
OK, so trying to convince a
visionary company to listen to

00:57:32.800 --> 00:57:35.460
your analytical type thinking.

00:57:35.460 --> 00:57:38.990
Number one, you need to get a
read on the character of the

00:57:38.990 --> 00:57:40.450
CEO of the company--

00:57:40.450 --> 00:57:41.600
of your visionary.

00:57:41.600 --> 00:57:43.340
Whoever the CEO is.

00:57:43.340 --> 00:57:46.130
They might be the CEO, they
might be the general manager

00:57:46.130 --> 00:57:47.590
of a business unit, if
the business units

00:57:47.590 --> 00:57:48.790
have a lot of autonomy.

00:57:48.790 --> 00:57:51.755
You've got to get a read on
their personality, and how

00:57:51.755 --> 00:57:53.310
insecure are they?

00:57:53.310 --> 00:57:55.250
Because what you can get is
you can get people who are

00:57:55.250 --> 00:57:58.410
visionaries who have a fair
amount of personal insecurity,

00:57:58.410 --> 00:58:01.320
where they view any challenge as
a personal threat to them.

00:58:01.320 --> 00:58:04.340
And that's just not a good place
to try to feed ideas to

00:58:04.340 --> 00:58:06.640
them, because they don't have
enough self confidence to be

00:58:06.640 --> 00:58:08.960
able to listen to dissenting
ideas.

00:58:08.960 --> 00:58:11.710
If they feel secure, though,
what you can do is you can

00:58:11.710 --> 00:58:14.700
feed it to them as this
is a way to make

00:58:14.700 --> 00:58:16.640
your vision even stronger.

00:58:16.640 --> 00:58:18.370
I'm not trying to replace
your vision.

00:58:18.370 --> 00:58:21.260
What I'm trying to do is test
it out against some things

00:58:21.260 --> 00:58:23.990
that will help you spot
potential blind spots.

00:58:23.990 --> 00:58:27.050
And by going through this
process of roadmapping,

00:58:27.050 --> 00:58:29.420
thinking through these things,
what we're going to produce is

00:58:29.420 --> 00:58:31.240
something that we will bring
straight to you-- we're not

00:58:31.240 --> 00:58:33.060
going to take to the whole
company first, we'll bring it

00:58:33.060 --> 00:58:34.290
right to you.

00:58:34.290 --> 00:58:38.380
And what we'll do is we will let
you think through it, and

00:58:38.380 --> 00:58:40.800
you can look at, oh, I hadn't
thought about this issue.

00:58:40.800 --> 00:58:42.260
Gee, I've got to reconsider
this.

00:58:42.260 --> 00:58:43.630
Or, yep, I've got to
work that one.

00:58:43.630 --> 00:58:45.530
Or no, here's why I think
you guys are wrong.

00:58:45.530 --> 00:58:48.580
But you will have a higher
percentage chance of success,

00:58:48.580 --> 00:58:49.660
because it's been tested.

00:58:49.660 --> 00:58:50.950
It's just like exercise.

00:58:50.950 --> 00:58:53.370
And usually these execs are
really into exercise.

00:58:53.370 --> 00:58:56.160
If you sell it like exercise--
this is mental exercise to try

00:58:56.160 --> 00:58:57.980
to make your ideas stronger--

00:58:57.980 --> 00:59:00.380
they'll tend to go for that,
as long as they have enough

00:59:00.380 --> 00:59:01.480
self confidence that
they don't feel

00:59:01.480 --> 00:59:02.430
threatened by that thing.

00:59:02.430 --> 00:59:03.170
Now, let me flip it around.

00:59:03.170 --> 00:59:06.730
Analytical companies tend very
often to be rather than top

00:59:06.730 --> 00:59:08.650
down, they tend to
be bottom up.

00:59:08.650 --> 00:59:10.620
So it'll be, I want
ideas to come up

00:59:10.620 --> 00:59:11.460
from within the company.

00:59:11.460 --> 00:59:13.680
I want those to boil up to us.

00:59:13.680 --> 00:59:16.150
I want to create processes by
which we get ideas internally,

00:59:16.150 --> 00:59:18.120
and we vet them, and other
things like that.

00:59:18.120 --> 00:59:21.010
To those executives, you sell
this roadmap thing as an

00:59:21.010 --> 00:59:24.920
additional process that will
produce better quality

00:59:24.920 --> 00:59:27.330
thinking around long
term opportunities.

00:59:27.330 --> 00:59:28.960
And you sell them on,
you know what?

00:59:28.960 --> 00:59:32.150
We prioritize short term easy
stuff much higher than we

00:59:32.150 --> 00:59:34.370
prioritize the long term
difficult stuff that might

00:59:34.370 --> 00:59:35.720
produce the big returns.

00:59:35.720 --> 00:59:38.870
That's a logical, analytical
view of the problem that they

00:59:38.870 --> 00:59:39.930
can buy into.

00:59:39.930 --> 00:59:42.060
And then what they'll say is,
OK, Mr. Smart Guy, what do we

00:59:42.060 --> 00:59:42.770
do about it?

00:59:42.770 --> 00:59:44.530
Well, we're going to run this
run this roadmap process that

00:59:44.530 --> 00:59:47.970
brings out those intuitive vague
ideas that people have

00:59:47.970 --> 00:59:50.720
that vets them and helps to
draw out scenarios of how

00:59:50.720 --> 00:59:53.000
things could develop in the
future so that you can view

00:59:53.000 --> 00:59:54.910
them as a more realistic
thing.

00:59:54.910 --> 00:59:57.760
You can get a better sense of
what might be possible, and

00:59:57.760 --> 00:59:59.200
you'll be able to think
ahead of where

00:59:59.200 --> 01:00:00.450
competitors are thinking.

01:00:00.450 --> 01:00:01.440
That's a way to hook them.

01:00:01.440 --> 01:00:05.480
OK so going by this process, I,
Samsung, can get someplace

01:00:05.480 --> 01:00:09.040
faster than the Nokias
of the world.

01:00:09.040 --> 01:00:10.870
And therefore, I'm going to have
a bigger advantage in the

01:00:10.870 --> 01:00:11.290
marketplace.

01:00:11.290 --> 01:00:11.530
Great.

01:00:11.530 --> 01:00:11.990
Let's do it.

01:00:11.990 --> 01:00:13.240
Let's go try it.

01:00:13.240 --> 01:00:15.530
And then it's a matter of
executing on it and making

01:00:15.530 --> 01:00:17.960
sure that they can see the
benefits of it over time.

01:00:17.960 --> 01:00:21.150
So work from their angle.

01:00:21.150 --> 01:00:23.920
Visionary companies tend to be
top down, so sell it from the

01:00:23.920 --> 01:00:25.580
top down as a way to
improve their own

01:00:25.580 --> 01:00:28.150
thinking through exercise.

01:00:28.150 --> 01:00:29.970
Analytical companies tend
to be bottom up.

01:00:29.970 --> 01:00:32.980
